In our framework, we suppose each node ui would adjust its discovery schedule every Œî time slots according to the energy

unit or application requirements, where Œî could be a large constant such as one day or one week. There are two main reasons. First, neighbor discover process should be executed many times. In many extant works, neighbor discovery is only

conducted once to initialize the network topology and they

assume such information will remain afterwards. However, some sensors may die when the energy is exhausted, or some new sensors may be deployed, they lead to the change of the original network. Thus, the nodes have to conduct the neighbor discovery process to re-construct the network. Second, the nodes can adjust the duty cycle dynamically. For example, the nodes can reduce the duty cycle to save energy as time goes on, thus we need to adjust the schedule to satisfy the duty cycle. In this paper, we assume the nodes could update the neighbor discovery schedule periodically to simplify the process.
We assume there are m different duty cycle levels as Œò = {Œ∏(1), Œ∏(2), . . . , Œ∏(m)} where Œ∏(i) > Œ∏(j) if i > j. At the beginning of each period of length Œî, each node chooses a corresponding duty cycle level by the remaining energy and the subsequent tasks. We deÔ¨Åne the adjustable neighbor discovery problem as:
Problem 2: Suppose node ui starts at time Œ¥i, denote the chosen duty cycle at time Œ¥i(d) = Œ¥i + d ¬∑ Œî (d ‚â• 0) as Œ∏i(d) ‚àà Œò, design the neighbor discovery schedule Si(d) = {si(t)|Œ¥i(d) ‚â§ t < Œ¥i(d + 1)} for node ui where:

si(t) =

0 if ui chooses state OF F 1 if ui chooses state ON

For any neighboring node uj starting at time Œ¥j, there exists Œ¥i(d) ‚â§ T < Œ¥i(d + 1) such that:

si(T ) = sj(T ) = 1

As stated in the problem, each node ui could choose an arbitrary duty cycle level Œ∏i(d) at the beginning of the d-th period, and it can discover the neighboring node uj no matter what duty cycle it chooses. The ultimate goal is to minimize the discovery latency between every pair of neighboring sensor nodes once any node changes the duty cycle level, no matter when the node changes and which duty cycle level is chosen. In this paper, we assume the nodes change the duty cycle periodically for simpliÔ¨Åcation.

