For any two neighboring nodes ui, uj, denote the duty cycles as Œ∏i, Œ∏j, and the corresponding prime sets as Pi = {pi(1), pi(2), . . . , pi(ki)}, Pj = {pj(1), pj(2), . . . , pj(kj)} respectively. The discovery can be guaranteed as the follow-
ing lemma. Since pi(1) cannot be equal to both pj(1) and pj(2), we may apply the Chinese Remainder Theorem [13] to guarantee that the nodes can discover each other in a short
time.
Lemma 3.1: Two neighboring nodes ui, uj can discover each other within L(i, j) time slots where:

L(i, j) ‚â§ min{pi(1) ¬∑ pj(2), pj(1) ¬∑ pi(2)}
Proof: Considering the two smallest primes pi(1), pi(2) and pj(1), pj(2) in each prime set, pi(1) cannot be equal to both pj(1) and pj(2). Suppose pi(1) = pj(2), from Alg. 1, node ui sets si(t) = 1 if there exists prime p ‚àà Pi such that t%p = 0. Therefore, both nodes turn on the radios in time slot T (from uj‚Äôs local time view) if the following equalities hold:
T + Œ¥ij ‚â° 0 mod pi(1) T ‚â° 0 mod pj(2)
According to the Chinese Remainder Theorem [13], such T ‚àà [0, pi(1)pj(2)) exists. Thus, the discovery latency L(i, j) is bounded by pi(1) ¬∑ pj(2). Similarly, L(i, j) is also bounded by pj(1) ¬∑ pi(2) time slots. Thus, the lemma holds.
Therefore, we can conclude the theorem as: Theorem 1: The prime set based algorithm can guarantee efÔ¨Åcient neighbor discovery no matter what duty cycle the nodes choose in each period.

